\par }{\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 The interpretation of Adorno\rquote s philosophy I offer here is shaped by two problems: the problem of the availability of the good, which bears on Adorno\rquote 
s ethics and social theory, and the problem of the consistency of Adorno\rquote s ethics with the central tenets of his philosophical negativism. I show that there is a way of construing the relation between the ineffable and the ethical in Adorno\rquote 
s philosophy, which provides an account of the availability of the good that is compatible with his philosophical negativism. }{\f40\fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 Naturally this is not a freestanding argument. }{
\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 It is an interpretation, one that is constrained by what I consider to be the most important, central and characteristic claims of Adorno\rquote s philosophy. The ancillar
y aim of this article is to take issue with a prevalent line of interpretation maintaining that Adorno\rquote s philosophy needlessly embraces paradox and aporia and thus lapses into irrationalism and mysticism.}{
\cs17\f40\fs20\super\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s16\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\cs17\f40\super\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 \chftn }{\f40\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903  Habermas describes the project of negative dialectics as \lquote a turn to the irrational\rquote . Habermas 1995: 37. H. Schn\'e4
delbach makes the same objection to Adorno. \lquote Dialektik als Vernunftkritik. Zur Konstruktion des Rationalen bei Adorno\rquote  in Habermas 1983: 9. }}}{\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903  This charge seems to be premised on a similarity b
etween Adorno\rquote s philosophical negativism and negative theology. Unlike many defenders of Adorno I do not deny that there is a similarity between a certain kind of negative theology and Adorno\rquote 
s philosophical concern with the ineffable. Properly understood, it throws light on his solution to the problem of the availability of the good. I do deny, however, that Adorno\rquote 
s negativism leads to any philosophically disreputable form of irrationalism or mysticism. 
\par }{\b\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 
\par 1.\tab \tab Three Central Theses of Adorno\rquote s Philosophy
\par }{\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 In order to see why Adorno\rquote s ethics are problematic we must briefly consider the three central theses that encapsulate his philosophical negativism.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 
