\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903  The second thesis is the key to understanding the first. Adorno thinks that his (and our) social world is radically evil. Throughout his writings Adorno never blushes at using terms like \lquote absolute evil
\rquote  (DA 171, HTS 62), \lquote radically evil\rquote  (ND 374 & 23 MCP 114-5) and \lquote the bad\rquote  [}{\i\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 das Schlechte}{\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 
] (ND 128). He thinks that social fabric of the post-war world, specifically America, Western Europe and the whole Eastern Bloc including the Soviet Union, is essentially corrupt or diseased [}{\i\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 Unheil}{
\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 ] (DE xv, DA 5 ND 128). 
\par }\pard \qj \fi720\li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 
This thesis is easy to misunderstand. Adorno does not claim that the social world is evil because it led to the death camps. True, Auschwitz, and all it stands for (MCP 101 & 104) is a central theme of Adorno\rquote s social phil
osophy and he often intimates that any culture which allowed such appalling things to happen must be deeply flawed. However, Auschwitz is only a very vivid and horrible example of the radical evil of the social world - the commodification and bureaucratis
ation of genocide. Other examples include the atom bomb and the Vietnam war (MCP}{\b\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903  }{\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 101,104,116).
\par Equally, it is a mistake to think that this is an exaggerated way of stating that bourgeois capitalism is iniquitous. Adorno is a Marxist and believes that capita
lism - the process of the reification of things and persons by which concrete use-values are reduced to abstract exchange-values - is nefarious.  However, he departs from Marx insofar as he holds that capitalism is only symptomatic of a more fundamental e
vil. For Adorno, the underlying cause of radical evil is not socio-economic: it resides in the form of rationality itself.}{\cs17\f40\fs20\super\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s16\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs17\f40\super\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 \chftn }{\f40\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903  Geuss 1999: 97.}}}{
\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903  
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 Adorno\rquote s use of the term \lquote radical evil\rquote  recalls Kant\rquote s in his }{
\i\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 Religion Within the Limits of Reason Alone}{\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 . Kant claims that evil is not a moral quality that can be appropriately attributed to an individual\rquote 
s character on the basis of his actions. Rather it is a metaphysical property of the will, which explains people\rquote s apparently natural predisposition voluntarily, through weakness, sel
fishness or wickedness, to act heteronomously by pursuing ends given by sensible inclinations.}{\cs17\f40\fs20\super\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s16\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs17\f40\super\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 \chftn }{\f40\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903 
 Kant 1960: 21 & 27. Some Neo-Platonists and Gnostics also believe that the mundane world is evil, but the parallel with Kant is stronger, since Adorno and Kant both equate evil with unfreedom and heteronomy. }}}{
\f40\fs20\insrsid13633421\charrsid10958903  For Adorno, evil refers to the widespread and systematic tendency for people to choose their own unfreedom by adjusting to and accepting socially given norms an
